00:40:23.840 --> 00:40:27.840
usually, though, it starts out with maybe R Markdown, maybe some interactive,

00:40:28.399 --> 00:40:33.840
like a Flex Dashboard that's maybe a little lighter weight. If it's something that's truly

00:40:33.840 --> 00:40:39.679
line of business, counts, volumes, things like that, or we have an existing QlikView app for,

00:40:39.679 --> 00:40:45.199
we'll push the work towards that side. So that's kind of our decision point, I think.

00:40:45.520 --> 00:40:51.840
Great, thank you. One more question for now is, how open is data access for your data science team

00:40:51.840 --> 00:40:59.840
within the organization? That is, yes. So our data science team, I definitely, and even our analysts,

00:40:59.840 --> 00:41:07.280
we are, it's fairly open. We have access to just about everything we need or we can get access to.

00:41:08.239 --> 00:41:14.320
We definitely have security on all of our data science teams. We have a lot of data science

00:41:14.879 --> 00:41:17.760
on all those different data sets, but the data science team,

00:41:18.320 --> 00:41:22.800
if we need some kind of access, we usually are able to get it. So it hasn't been an issue.

00:41:24.479 --> 00:41:26.000
Great, thanks, Chris. Yeah.

00:41:28.239 --> 00:41:33.439
So I'm going to spend maybe just five more minutes talking about something we're currently working on.

00:41:34.879 --> 00:41:43.120
We're thinking about, in the hospital, adding or kind of moving around some of the units and what

00:41:43.120 --> 00:41:47.600
kind of cohorts of patients they're responsible for. And this is coming out of the need for,

00:41:47.600 --> 00:41:53.600
as we know, there's kind of a mental health crisis maybe coming our way. And it's certainly

00:41:53.600 --> 00:41:58.719
true for children as well. So we'd like to think about maybe, do we add a mental health

00:41:58.719 --> 00:42:04.639
or behavioral health unit at the hospital, for instance, or do we partner or what do we do?

00:42:05.360 --> 00:42:13.280
And so they had a couple ideas about what maybe we could do with groups of patients and placing

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:16.479
them on different units in the hospital. But we didn't really have a good way to say,

00:42:17.360 --> 00:42:22.959
all right, well, A, we know that outpatient volumes are increasing and inpatient volumes

00:42:22.959 --> 00:42:29.840
are probably decreasing. That's a standard trend in healthcare. But we didn't know how,

00:42:30.479 --> 00:42:37.120
what percentage of maybe a base year, like say we take 2019 volumes and we think, well,

00:42:37.120 --> 00:42:45.439
what percentage of 2019 volumes will we recover in 2021 because of the pandemic? And so we created a

00:42:45.439 --> 00:42:52.800
tool that used to kind of a Monte Carlo simulation of different ways that we could look at slicing

00:42:52.800 --> 00:42:57.120
up these volumes. And we did it by cohorts of kids. And then we placed cohorts of kids

00:42:57.120 --> 00:43:03.919
on units and projected out a year, basically using the different parameters that I was just

00:43:03.919 --> 00:43:09.760
referring to as far as sampling percentages. We know that, let's just say 2019 volumes, we know

00:43:09.760 --> 00:43:16.479
that maybe we're going to see 90% of the volume we saw in 2019 and 2021, or maybe 2021 and 2022.

00:43:17.439 --> 00:43:23.280
But we know that that volume isn't going to be exactly the same kinds of kids. It isn't all

00:43:23.280 --> 00:43:28.159
going to be cardiac cases or just, you know, going to be different kinds of cases or maybe

00:43:28.159 --> 00:43:32.959
broken bones or whatever. So we wanted to try and simulate a bunch of times just using Monte

00:43:32.959 --> 00:43:38.320
Carlo, of course, simulate a bunch of times and look at what would be a likely scenario.

00:43:38.320 --> 00:43:43.280
And then will it fit with our new placement model, knowing that some of the beds are going to be

00:43:43.280 --> 00:43:49.840
carved out for this new unit. So that's what this app was for. And this is one that's still ongoing

00:43:49.919 --> 00:43:55.199
because we're working with the hospital leadership to understand the different models they're

00:43:55.199 --> 00:44:00.399
suggesting and to see if it'll even make sense from this, looking at it kind of historical data

00:44:00.399 --> 00:44:05.679
and this modeling. So the very first step we did, of course, was show them what's going on with the

00:44:05.679 --> 00:44:10.000
hospital, right? Where do kids get admitted to? Where do they discharge from? And we actually

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:14.639
track this more granularly to look at all the units they might stop. And if they go to imaging

00:44:14.639 --> 00:44:19.679
or lab, but we want to understand the movement throughout the hospital. And this is just kind

00:44:19.679 --> 00:44:24.959
of a retrospective look at that using Plotly with the kind of in a Sankey diagram here.

00:44:26.800 --> 00:44:31.199
At the same time, we also looked at all the historical data. And you'll see now it's just

00:44:31.199 --> 00:44:37.199
kind of an interesting chart because we're showing what we call tarp levels. So if we get up to like

00:44:38.159 --> 00:44:43.520
17 or 18, here we go yellow, that might mean we might need to change staffing or resource planning,

00:44:43.520 --> 00:44:50.560
or we may think about having to move kids to a different unit, possibly. And this distribution

00:44:50.560 --> 00:44:57.840
here is an example of all the hourly census values that we've generated for the hospital.

00:44:57.840 --> 00:45:03.600
So and we've done this by unit, we did it by service, and we did it by kind of cohort of kids

00:45:03.600 --> 00:45:10.879
based on like diagnosis and attending providers. And again, so we're looking at how can we find

00:45:10.879 --> 00:45:16.399
out what is a representative way to look at the populations before we ever talked about doing any

00:45:16.399 --> 00:45:22.639
kind of simulation. So again, this is a retrospective look, look at that. And then we

00:45:22.639 --> 00:45:28.000
decided, all right, now that we have all this data, and we have these distributions, and we understand

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:32.959
the distribution of kids and where they fit, that's kind of do this Monte Carlo simulation,

00:45:32.959 --> 00:45:38.959
right? And then project these cohorts going to planned units and look at kind of the activity

00:45:38.959 --> 00:45:43.679
map to say, when are we going to be at that red tarp level, where we know that we won't have

00:45:43.679 --> 00:45:50.399
enough staff or enough beds for a given unit. And then we can kind of score the different units

00:45:50.399 --> 00:45:55.439
and the different models to understand that this model is going to fit or not. And here's your

00:45:55.439 --> 00:46:02.320
likelihood. And here's your confidence interval, saying this is what we think it might look like

00:46:02.320 --> 00:46:07.120
for a given year. And so we have a couple of different models created. And then we can kind

00:46:07.120 --> 00:46:13.679
of just run these scenarios. And so we've been helping them in this kind of a unique way, I think,

00:46:13.679 --> 00:46:19.439
of doing this simulation just to understand, does this even make sense to suggest a model like this,

00:46:20.399 --> 00:46:25.280
which is what we ended up doing. So we're just currently in this, we're working on this right now.

00:46:25.280 --> 00:46:30.560
This is kind of just like a work in progress. But I thought it was interesting that we started to

00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:35.600
apply, like at first we did the initial heat maps where we just looked at volumes, but it wasn't a

00:46:35.600 --> 00:46:41.520
lot of meaning until we applied that tarp level on top to say, yeah, when it gets to be this dark,

00:46:41.520 --> 00:46:45.600
it actually is a red tarp. And so we should be concerned at the end of the year. And this is

00:46:45.600 --> 00:46:51.360
like flu season, right, where it's starting to be worse. And so we started to think about

00:46:52.159 --> 00:46:56.560
different ways to visualize that same thing. We actually went and also did it,

00:46:56.560 --> 00:47:01.919
instead of a heat map, say how green is green and how red is red. And so we actually put that

00:47:01.919 --> 00:47:07.280
just across a histogram like this. So we could kind of look at how deep into the red we were

00:47:07.280 --> 00:47:12.399
going or how green we really were to know if we had capacity, or if a unit could maybe take

00:47:12.399 --> 00:47:18.800
patients from a different unit as we start to think about kind of pop off units for when we

00:47:18.800 --> 00:47:26.239
get to high volume situations. I think that was all I wanted to cover with that right now.

00:47:26.239 --> 00:47:30.639
There's definitely more work. We did some work on patient churn. I think maybe that would be a great

00:47:31.439 --> 00:47:37.360
segue for another talk at a different time. But we definitely are using Shiny heavily. And this

00:47:37.360 --> 00:47:41.679
one is, like I said, one of the most recent apps we've done. And so a lot of our learning has kind

00:47:41.679 --> 00:47:47.040
of fallen into this one. We've kind of switched over to Plotly now for most of our interactive

00:47:47.040 --> 00:47:52.159
charts away from High Charter. I think the licensing is a little nicer and the flexibility

00:47:52.159 --> 00:47:56.320
we're getting with Plotly, where we can do the Sankey diagrams, we can do these kind of charts,

00:47:56.320 --> 00:48:01.360
and we can do a lot more manipulation of what we show in visualization.

00:48:02.959 --> 00:48:06.959
I did have just one final slide, probably just talking about scoring and measurement.

00:48:06.959 --> 00:48:11.280
When we think about data science, I'm always thinking about how to score things or how to

00:48:11.280 --> 00:48:16.399
put things in context for people. And so we actually do look at scoring the individual

00:48:16.399 --> 00:48:22.080
units and then providing a rolled up score for the entire facility, which is our Milwaukee

00:48:22.080 --> 00:48:28.959
campus hospital. So we actually do that same kind of level of scoring here. And then we actually

00:48:28.959 --> 00:48:34.560
will build up some kind of report cards for the different models that get suggested.

